<p><b>E-democracy</b>, a combination of the words "<a href="/wiki/Electronics" title="Electronics">electronic</a>" and "<a href="/wiki/Democracy" title="Democracy">democracy</a>," comprises the use of electronic <a href="/wiki/Communication" title="Communication">communications</a> <a href="/wiki/Technologies" title="Technologies" class="mw-redirect">technologies</a> such as the <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a> in enhancing democratic processes within a democratic <a href="/wiki/Republic" title="Republic">republic</a> or <a href="/wiki/Representative_democracy" title="Representative democracy">representative democracy</a>. It is a political development still in its infancy, as well as the subject of much debate and activity within government, civic-oriented groups and <a href="/wiki/Society" title="Society">societies</a> around the world.</p>
<p>The term is both descriptive and prescriptive. Typically, the kinds of enhancements sought by proponents of e-democracy are framed in terms of making processes more <a href="/wiki/Accessibility" title="Accessibility">accessible</a>; making <a href="/wiki/Citizenship" title="Citizenship">citizen</a> <a href="/wiki/Participation_(decision_making)" title="Participation (decision making)">participation</a> in <a href="/wiki/Public_policy" title="Public policy">public policy</a> <a href="/wiki/Decision-making" title="Decision-making" class="mw-redirect">decision-making</a> more expansive and direct so as to enable broader influence in policy outcomes as more individuals involved could yield smarter policies; increasing transparency and accountability; and keeping the government closer to the <a href="/wiki/Consent_of_the_governed" title="Consent of the governed">consent of the governed</a>, thereby increasing its <a href="/wiki/Political_legitimacy" title="Political legitimacy" class="mw-redirect">political legitimacy</a>. E-democracy includes within its scope <i><a href="/wiki/Electronic_voting" title="Electronic voting">electronic voting</a></i>, but has a much wider span than this single aspect of the democratic process.</p>
<p>E-democracy is also sometimes referred to as <b>cyberdemocracy</b> or <b>digital democracy</b>.</p>
